evaluation.expected_answer: More aggressive suppression does not help fires end faster but helps fires affect less buildings.
evaluation.actual_answer:
Regression analysis of suppression aggression (dominant_strategy_75_s) on fire outcomes:
1. Duration relationship: Coefficient = 13.3817 (95% CI: [12.6212, 14.0938]), R² = 0.284. More aggressive suppression is associated with shorter fire duration.
2. Building impact relationship: Coefficient = -103.9335 (95% CI: [-192.5142, -15.0709]), R² = 0.000. Aggression shows no significant relationship with building impact.
Conclusion: More aggressive suppression contributes to faster containment (reduced duration) but does not significantly affect the number of buildings threatened.
